Price (1936) erected MazocraeoidesPrice, 1936 with Mazocraeoides georgeiPrice, 1936 from Pomolobus pseudoharengus of Brazil as the type species. PseudoctocotylaYamaguti, 1938 was considered as a synonym of this genus ( Sproston 1946 ). Mazocraeoides is characterized by the absence of a true haptor, arrangement of clamps along the body margin, complicated structure of the clamp comprising five sclerites, the formation of labiatum by the fusion of scleritum postero-supplementarium and arcuatum posterius, the winged antero-supplementarium, complicated configuration of medio-basale and the occurrence of a single testis ( Mamaev 1982 ). So far 25 species including the type species were described under this genus. Eleven species of the genus were reported from Indian fishes. However, considering that the descriptions provided for many of the Indian species were inadequate, eight species were put under the category of ‘ species inquirendae ’ ( Williams 1988 ;
Zhang et al. 1998
).

Clupeiform fishes were collected from the line catches of fishermen at Fishing Harbour, Visakhapatnam coast, Bay of Bengal (1744’N, 8323’E). The fish were brought to the laboratory in the fresh condition, the gills were separated and examined for monogeneans under a stereozoom binocular microscope. Specimens of Mazocraeoides spp. found on the gills were collected in saline. A few specimens were mounted in glycerine ammonium picrate medium of Malmberg (1970) for the study of the hard parts. Some specimens were fixed in 95% ethanol for DNA extraction and the remaining specimens were fixed in alcohol-formaldehyde- acetic acid (AFA) solution, stained with alum carmine, dehydrated through a graded ethanol series, cleared in creosote and prepared as whole mounts in Canada balsam. Illustrations were drawn with the aid of a camera lucida. Measurements are in micrometres (µm) and are expressed as the mean followed by the range in parentheses. The nomenclature of clamp sclerites proposed by Mamaev (1981) is adopted here. Holotypes , paratypes and voucher specimens are deposited in Zoological Survey of India (ZSI), Kolkata, India and paratypes in the Natural History Museum, London ( NHMUK ). DNA extraction and sequencing were performed according to the procedure followed earlier (
Sailaja et al ., 2016
). The 28S rDNA sequences were deposited in the GenBank database.
